<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In contrast to the usual tales of gloom and destruction shown in so many
wildlife programmes, today's Survival promises a story of success and hope.
Conservationists were worried about the development of Stansted airport but
today, a year after the new airport opened, orchids thrive at the end of the
runway, rabbits play, owls hunt for voles and mice and there are still
kestrels in residence (7.30 ITV).
Beginning in the desert cities of Samarkand and Bokhara on the Old Silk
Road, Assignment reports from central Asia following the disintegration of
the Soviet Union. The newly independent states of Uzbekistan and Tadjikistan
are bankrupt and Moslem fundamentalism is resurgent. The programme asks
whether any political party can control the social forces unleashed by the
end of Soviet rule (7.45 BBC2).
At 8.00, Channel 4 has a profile of former war photographer Don McCullin who
now lives in Somerset and concentrates on landscape and still-life
photography.
ITV's downbeat series about real life detection, Murder Squad ends with the
views of two men now serving life sentences as a result of investigations
featured earlier in the series (9.00).
</TEXT>
