FT  17 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Pledge on Scottish Gas and Telecom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Liberal Democrats would create a Scottish Telecom and Scottish Gas by
breaking up the privatised monopolies if they were elected.
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Scottish Liberal Democrat leader, said the move would be
part of a pledge to stimulate competition included in the manifesto launched
yesterday. The new Scottish utility companies would not involve
re-nationalisation. Shareholders had been given adequate warning. 'The
prospectus made it quite clear the Liberal Democrats were committed to
breaking up British Gas,' Mr Bruce declared.
Parts of British Steel would be transferred to Scottish ownership. The
manifesto mentions development of a site at Hunterston, which it says has
the potential to be a centre for an integrated Scottish steel industry.
Home rule for Scotland is a central issue in the manifesto, though Mr Bruce
stressed Scottish voters would be paying attention to questions affecting
the whole UK. The Liberal Democrat proposals for home rule were part of a
thorough reform of the political system, and so would guarantee fair
representation for Scotland. Other proposals include a Scottish ministry of
justice and a Scottish environmental protection agency.
