<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Royal Mail plans to consult unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL MAIL, the letters arm of the Post Office, is to give union
representatives a say in a wide range of business issues, including prices,
standards of service and new technology.
The move is the first by a large UK employer to set up a formal national
worker participation scheme since experiments in industrial democracy in the
late 1970s. Employee consultation has been out of fashion for over a decade.
Employers have generally sought to restrict union influence to pay and
conditions.
Royal Mail's unusual step is part of an industrial relations shake-up
affecting about 180,000 employees. The agreement has been hailed by union
leaders and management as a blueprint for other parts of industry.
A new national joint committee will be attended each month by senior Royal
Mail managers and national union officials. It is expected that Mr Bill
Cockburn, Royal Mail managing director, and Mr Alan Tuffin, general
secretary of the Union of Communication Workers, will regularly take part.
Mr Jerry Cope, Royal Mail's director of personnel, said the framework
provided a 'third model' for industry in the UK. Old-fashioned public sector
organisations had been stuck with excessive levels of consultation and very
slow rates of change. Other employers went to the opposite extreme and
attempted to exclude unions altogether, he said.
Royal Mail did not believe either model was appropriate for the 21st
century, said Mr Cope. If unions were pushed into the corner, 'every so
often they come out and bite you'. The Post Office has suffered from poor
industrial relations in the past, though the number of unofficial disputes
has declined.
Both sides stressed that involvement of unions in business issues was not a
return to the short-lived experiments in industrial democracy in the Post
Office and British Steel Corporation in the late 1970s. There would be no
question of 'co-management', said Mr Cope.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
