<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Mather quits as head of troubled IEA think-tank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GRAHAM MATHER has quit as general director of the troubled Institute of
Economic Affairs, after a new row within the faction-riven rightwing
think-tank.
Mr Mather, 37, took his decision yesterday after details of a private
agreement between him and the board, involving his departure at the end of
the year, were leaked to the press.
His resignation comes amid fresh evidence of renewed fighting between
factions - Thatcherite loyalists in the Conservative party, represented by
the anti-European Community Bruges Group, and forces more in tune with the
approach to Britain's EC membership taken by Mr John Major, the prime
minister.
Supporters of Mr Mather, who took up the post in January 1987, believe he is
the victim of a long-standing campaign to undermine him.
Last year, Lord Harris of High Cross and Mr Arthur Seldon - two founder
members - threatened to quit the board after Mr Mather endorsed publications
backing a more positive attitude to the EC.
In a compromise 'truce' between the IEA's two factions last September, it
was agreed that Lord Harris and Mr Seldon would remain on the board and the
general director would stay in his post.
But controversy continued to dog the institute following Mr Mather's backing
for new policy proposals, including the investigation of further proposed
market-oriented reforms of Whitehall and Westminster.
The revelation that Mr Mather planned to leave at the end of the year
prompted him to give three months' notice. 'There is clearly no long term
future for any think-tank riven by internal faction fighting,' he said last
night. 'I do believe that the work for which I have stood at the IEA - the
extension of market solutions to European political problems and the advance
of markets into government itself - is worthwhile and has a future.'
Mr Mather, a solicitor who first came to national prominence as head of
policy at the Institute of Directors, plans to start a new think-tank, the
London Institute for Economic and Policy Studies. It will take a positive
view of a decentralised EC, look at constitutional reforms of the machinery
of government and the extension of market principles into public services
and examine the economic powers of regulators.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-3102</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCPB5AENFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920316
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Markets await grim week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MARKETS are braced for a week of more grim news on the UK economy as the
first full week of the election campaign coincides with the release of a
string of monthly economic indicators.
The release of the retail prices index on Friday is expected to show a fall
in the annual inflation rate from 4.1 per cent in January to 4 per cent last
month.
The main focus of the week, however, will be Thursday's unemployment
figures. These are expected to show that unemployment rose by 35,000 in
February, the 23rd consecutive monthly rise.
Uncertainty about the outcome of the election, with weekend polls continuing
to point towards a hung parliament, is again likely to affect financial
markets.
The FT-SE 100 index fell nearly 100 points in the wake of the Budget on
Tuesday to finish the week at 2,476.
Meanwhile, pressure on sterling, which closed at DM2.85 on Friday, its
lowest level for the week, has virtually ruled out any prospect of a cut in
interest rates during the election campaign.
Job prospects were highlighted yesterday in a survey by Manpower, the
employment agency, which found that more big employers were expecting to
shed jobs than create new ones this year.
While prospects in manufacturing appeared to be holding up, banking showed a
continuing deterioration, with a net 19 per cent of banking employers
forecasting job cuts, it said.
The survey of 2,074 employers showed that prospects were worst in London.
Employers in Scotland were the most optimistic.
Yesterday, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said that, while unemployment
would 'continue to rise for some months yet', jobs would result from last
week's Budget.
'Anything that helps us to fight inflation and assist recovery is a Budget
that helps to create employment,' he said.
Other figures this week will provide little respite for the government.
Industrial production is expected to show a further fall.
But there may be some comfort for the government in Wednesday's retail sales
figures for February. The City is predicting flat sales between January and
February. But a survey by the Confederation of British Industry last week
showed a slight rise in sales for the seventh month running.
The week ahead, Page 12
Gilts depressed, Page 24
Currencies, Page 31
</TEXT>
