<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Election 92: Pledge on value of pound rejected
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS executives appear unconvinced that Labour's oft-stated
determination to maintain the value of sterling would be sustainable once it
secured power.
Three quarters predict that a victory for Mr Neil Kinnock would lead to a
rise in interest rates as sterling's value fell against the D-Mark - a fall
predicted by the same number.
In spite of Mr Kinnock's pledge that he would hold sterling's present parity
within the exchange rate mechanism, 71 per cent forecast that a devaluation
would be 'very likely' or 'fairly likely'.
Only 25 per cent believe that the foreign exchange markets would allow Mr
Kinnock to keep his pledge.
By contrast, only 8 per cent predict that Mr John Major would devalue, with
89 per cent expecting a Conservative government to stick with the present
ERM parity.
The view that Mr Major's return to Downing Street would be good for sterling
 -46 per cent believe its value would increase and the same number that it
would stay about the same - translates into a similarly optimistic
assessment of prospects for borrowing costs.
Some 57 per cent believe that a newly elected Tory government could cut
interest rates, with 35 per cent anticipating they would stay the same and
only 7 per per cent forecasting an increase.
The stark division between the two parties narrows when businesses are asked
how the election might affect their companies' investment intentions, but
the Conservatives still retain a strong advantage.
With Mr Major re-elected, 31 per cent would anticipate investing more in
Britain against the 63 per cent expecting investment to stay the same.
Some 65 per cent say their plans would be unaffected by a Labour victory,
but only 4 per cent would increase investment spending.
For 26 per cent, Mr Kinnock's entry into Downing Street would be a signal to
cut investment.
</TEXT>
