<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Irish ayes and the Chicago float vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS perfectly clear who could win the Democratic party's presidential
primary in Illinois tomorrow, writes Jurek Martin. His name is Pat O'Connor,
he comes from Chicago's 40th ward and he would win, if he were running,
because he had easily the largest float in Saturday's St Patrick's Day
parade.
National politicians are not really welcome at this celebration of Irishness
by Chicago's policemen, plumbers, pipefitters and social club members. The
three Democratic candidates stayed away, not only because none can afford
contracting pneumonia from Windy City at this stage. Pat Buchanan was going
to appear but spent the morning with Ukrainians instead.
Their supporters were out working the crowds, though hopelessly outnumbered
by those running for local office. By the number of placards seen and
leaflets collected, Bill Clinton will beat Paul Tsongas here easily, with
Jerry Brown nowhere, but this is hardly a scientific measurement.
More reliable was a weekend Chicago Sun-Times poll giving the governor of
Arkansas 48 per cent, the former senator from Massachusetts 21 per cent and
the former governor of California 7 per cent. It also had President Bush
overwhelming Mr Buchanan by 79-15 per cent on the Republican side. The
Mason-Dixon poll in neighbouring Michigan, which also votes tomorrow, told a
similar tale, with Mr Clinton at 48 per cent, Mr Tsongas 22 per cent and Mr
Brown 11 per cent. But most ward bosses were more interested in local races
for office.
</TEXT>
