<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Business chiefs want decisive Tory win: FT survey indicates
fear of sterling devaluation within ERM under Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S business leaders want a decisive Conservative victory on April 9,
fearing that the election of a Labour government would lead to a falling
pound and higher borrowing costs.
In a survey of board-level executives conducted by MORI for the Financial
Times, seven out of 10 predict that Mr Neil Kinnock's entry into Downing
Street would be followed by a devaluation of sterling within the Exchange
Rate Mechanism. Three-quarters of those surveyed believe that interest rates
would rise.
Only 49 per cent, however, say they are satisfied 'with the way the
government is running the country'.
Asked to say who would make the better chancellor, 46 per cent opt for
Labour's Mr John Smith against the 39 per cent who prefer Mr Norman Lamont,
the present incumbent.
Some 8 out of 10 of the executives, drawn from many of the country's largest
companies, say that an inconclusive election resulting in a coalition
government would be bad for the country.
A slightly smaller proportion - 6 out of 10 - added that such an outcome
would also damage their business.
The business leaders are not in buoyant mood; nor are they entirely happy
with the present government.
Instead, their responses underline deep concern about the impact of the
recession. Only 29 per cent accept the Conservative claim that Mr John
Major's return to Downing Street would speed up economic recovery.
Nearly two-thirds believe that the prime minister's re-election would make
little difference to the pace of any upturn.
But the clearest message of the survey - published on the day that Mr Smith
plans to unveil in his shadow Budget a range of measures to boost industrial
investment and training - is that in the highly-charged atmosphere of a
general election, the business community is unwilling to give public backing
to Labour's economic strategy.
Mr Smith has been joined repeatedly by Mr Kinnock in emphasising that a
Labour government would not devalue sterling within the ERM. But the
executives appear to have concluded that they would be unable to resist
speculation against the pound.
On overall economic management, 87 per cent say they prefer the
Conservatives against only 3 per cent who are convinced by the alternatives
offered by the main opposition party.
Despite Mr Smith's promise of new tax incentives for investment projects -
which he plans to spell out in detail today - a quarter of the respondents
suggest their companies might reduce their investment spending if Labour
were elected. Some 31 per cent say Mr Major's return to Downing Street would
bring a rise in their companies' capital spending in Britain.
The respondents to the survey - drawn from the FT top 500 companies - are
avowedly Conservative supporters.
Only 1 per cent of those surveyed plan to vote for the Labour party on April
9 against the 92 per cent who say they will back the Conservatives.
Predictably perhaps, 93 per cent say that Mr Major would make a better prime
minister than Mr Kinnock.
Only Mr Smith among Labour holders of the main economic portfolios outpoints
his opposite number.
Mr Michael Howard, the employment secretary, and Mr Peter Lilley, the trade
and industry secretary, both outpoint Mr Tony Blair and Mr Gordon Brown,
their respective shadows.
Survey details, Page 8
</TEXT>
