<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Opposition'Budget' to offer tax cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR will today try to 'trump' the Budget by offering an alternative
tax-cutting scheme under which personal allowances would more than double
and the National Insurance contributions (NICs) structure would be altered.
Party officials said its tax and benefits plan, due to be announced by Mr
John Smith, the shadow chancellor, will make almost nine out of 10 families
better off through changes targeted at the very poor and families on average
incomes. They also hinted that the proposed 50p top rate of income tax would
affect only those earning more than Pounds 40,000 a year.
Yesterday, Mr John Major, the prime minister, used a BBC radio interview to
accuse the Liberal Democrats and Labour of having a 'a fetish' for tax rises
with very damaging implications for individuals and business.
His claim was firmly denied by Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat
leader. While his party was ready to raise standard-rate tax by 1p to pay
for better education programmes, Mr Ashdown insisted: 'We want taxes to be
as low as they possibly can.'
Mr Smith's scheme is intended to counter repeated accusations by senior
Conservatives that his pledge to scrap the new 20p tax band amounts to
increased taxes for the low-paid.
It would raise allowances by more than double the 4.5 per cent annual
inflation rate taking 750,000 people out of tax at a cost to the Treasury
expected to be more than Pounds 800m. A central element in the scheme is the
proposed abolition of the first band of NICs which imposes a 2 per cent levy
on the first tranche of income of all those earning more than Pounds 52 a
week.
It is also understood that Mr Smith is reconsidering his plan to apply a 9
per cent National Insurance Contribution levy on unearned income above
Pounds 3,000 to allow a more generous tax-free threshold.
But Labour has abandoned a proposal to phase in the removal of the ceiling
above which taxpayers stop paying NICs, currently about Pounds 21,000 of
taxable income - the ceiling would be removed in Labour's first Budget.
A Labour party official said the 'unprecedented' plan was an
election-winning Budget that would kill the claim that Labour was the party
of high taxation. 'The average family is going to be better off than they
are under what Lamont offered last week,' he said.
Yesterday, Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, insisted: 'No Labour party
that I ever lead will disadvantage people who are on medium or on lower
incomes.'
But his claims in a TV-am interview that Britain would have been better off
had Labour won the 1983 election provoked derision from Tory cabinet
ministers.
'You simply cannot trust him when he says he really has abandoned all the
cranky notions that Labour argued so passionately for in their 1983
programme,' Mr Chris Patten, Tory chairman, said.
Tory campaigners were taking heart from the warm reception given to Mr Major
at a weekend party rally in Torquay. Addressing a Conservative central
council meeting, he ruled out devolution for Scotland and dismissed the
Liberal Democrats' insistence on electoral reform.
Gloomy economic news is expected this week as a string of monthly indicators
is released in the first full week of the election campaign. Markets await
grim week, Page 20
</TEXT>
