<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Election 1992
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
'The City can call off its panic this morning. There is no certainty that
Labour will win the election. That was last week's fashionable whisper,'
writes Joe Rogaly on Page 7
With 25 days to April 9, the FT will offer its unique brand of news,
analysis and comment. Joe Rogaly will write daily.  Barry Riley will keep a
regular watch on the City. A specially constructed FT Election Stock Index
will track the market's verdict.  Philip Stephens leads a team of political
reporters stationed in the country's key constituencies. FT foreign
correspondents will ask: how much does the world care who holds the keys to
Downing Street?
