<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Slaughters tops league table of profitability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SLAUGHTER and May, the City solicitors, has emerged as the UK's most
profitable law firm last year according to a league table of earnings
published by the magazine Legal Business.
Slaughter and May had average net profits per partner of Pounds 377,000 on a
turnover of Pounds 113m and profits per fee earner (lawyer) of Pounds
65,000. The firm has 542 fee earners.
Its nearest rival was Linklaters &amp; Paines with profits per partner of Pounds
349,000 on a turnover of Pounds 144m and profits per fee earner of Pounds
69,000. Linklaters has 692 lawyers.
The UK's largest law firm, Clifford Chance, not surprisingly had the biggest
turnover of Pounds 232m. With more than 200 partners and 1,122 fee earners
its profits per partner were Pounds 278,000.
Most of the top 10 most profitable firms had gross fee revenues of about
Pounds 1m per partner, according to the legal business statistics.
The magazine says it has had the co-operation of partners in the vast
majority of firms in compiling its figures, although there was a 'handful'
of firms for which it made 'informed guesses'.
None of the firms included in the league table would admit yesterday to
having co-operated with the magazine. Categorical denials of co-operation
were given by Slaughter and May, Freshfields, Lovell White Durrant, Allen &amp;
Overy, Linklaters &amp; Paines and Clifford Chance. No firm was prepared to
comment on the accuracy of the figures, however.
The magazine stresses that profits per partner did not represent take-home
pay. There are a few senior partners in London firms who earn more than
Pounds 1m a year but in general earnings for partners in the top firms range
from about Pounds 200,000 a year for junior partners to Pounds 500,000 for
senior partners, it says.
Most large law firms operate a 'lockstep system' which means their earnings
are capped after a certain number of years in the partnership. Also, in many
firms partners are expected to plough back some of their 'draw' to provide
working capital.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
