<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Election 92: Support for Major seen at 93 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE only surprise in the assessment of the relative qualities of the two
party leaders is just how overwhelming is the backing for Mr John Major. The
present prime minister is preferred by 93 per cent against the 1 per cent
backing Mr Neil Kinnock.
But there is an unwelcome message in the survey for Mr Norman Lamont. Only
39 per cent believe he is the best choice for No 11 Downing Street against
the 46 per cent prepared to forgive Mr John Smith his party affiliation and
say that he would make the better chancellor.
Mr Smith is particularly popular among executive of companies with a
turnover of between Pounds 500m and Pounds 2bn, where his rating jumps to 56
per cent, while the very biggest companies are kinder towards Mr Lamont.
Elsewhere, Mr Michael Howard scores for his implacable opposition to the
minimum wage and to any increase in the powers of unions by winning the
preference of 69 per cent for the job of employment secretary. Mr Tony
Blair, the young star of the Labour front bench gets the vote of only 14 per
cent.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow trade and industry secretary and a strong
contender for the future party leadership, does better, with 33 per cent
backing him for the cabinet post. But the present incumbent at the
Department of Trade and Industry, Mr Peter Lilley, is still comfortably
ahead with the support of 45 per cent.
</TEXT>
