<HEADLINE>
FT  16 MAR 92 / Polish minister seeks IMF backing for budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Andrzej Olechowski, Poland's finance minister, flew to Washington
yesterday to seek support from the International Monetary Fund, the World
Bank and the US government for his tough budget policies.
Mr Olechowski will seek IMF assurances that the budget, which foresees a Zl
65,500bn deficit amounting to 5 per cent of GDP, would form a basis on which
to renegotiate the terms of Poland's Dollars 1.6bn three-year extended
facility.
That was suspended last autumn when Poland's previous government failed to
meet the Fund's performance criteria on its budget deficit and expansion of
domestic credit.
Mr Olechowski will also be looking to the World Bank to ease the conditions
under which Dollars 1bn of credit committed to Poland and due this year can
be drawn.
Mr Olechowski needs international support when he returns on Wednesday to
present the draft budget to a centre-right cabinet aghast at the prospect of
major cuts in spending plans.
A more demanding test awaits the finance minister next month when he will
present the budget to parliament.
</TEXT>
