<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / Sex and the single company: Dominic Lawson thinks that a
womens' magazine and a condom company make strange bedfellows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINIC LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the few perks in the otherwise austere life of a magazine editor is
that he or she is constantly being sent free copies of every other magazine.
The perk lies in not reading them. But sometimes curiosity overcomes
judgement. Elle magazine caters for curious editors by publishing a special
'SEX' section. Just in case we don't get the point, the word SEX is written
in red letters six inches high. It's size that counts. But one should not be
flippant. Elle has recently forged links with The Guardian newspaper and
must, therefore, be taken seriously, if not actually believed. 'Imagine,'
the SEX section begins, 'a woman standing straight and proud, facing the
world head-on. In one hand she carries a briefcase, symbolising her control
over her working life; in the other she brandishes a vibrator and a packet
of condoms   . in the 1990s this woman is becoming a reality.' This, of
course, is absolutely right. Women walking around with symbolic briefcases
in one hand, and condoms and vibrators in the other are a common sight these
days, and I'm surprised no one has noted this fact before now. Presumably
the condoms these women brandish are manufactured by Durex. You see, Durex
has sponsored the Elle SEX survey, and it would be ungrateful to brandish
imaginary condoms made by a rival company. Durex, naturally, would like
every woman of child bearing age to run around brandishing its wares, and it
pays to advertise; the subliminal message, as they say in the Ad Biz, is
that if you don't do Durex you do get AIDS.
But not all the readers of Elle, sadly, have yet absorbed this vital
message. 'Has AIDS changed the way we love?' it shrieks: 'A staggering 54
per cent of our sample did not consider themselves at risk from AIDS.
Understandable perhaps, given that many of them are in relationships, but
worrying, given the statistics on fidelity. Even more concerning is the fact
that over a third claim not to have changed their sexual behaviour because
of HIV/AIDS.'
I do indeed find it staggering that 46 per cent of Elle readers consider
themselves at risk from AIDS, and that two thirds of its readership have
changed their sexual behaviour because of HIV/AIDS. The most recent
statistics from anonymous tests carried out in British ante-natal clinics
show the incidence of the HIV virus among women in central London as 0.04
per cent or one in 4,000. Outside central London the incidence of HIV is
0.016 per cent, or one in 16,000. These, remember, are figures from
ante-natal clinics, essentially women between the ages of 18 and 38. Such
tests among the total female population would most likely show an even more
minuscule incidence of the HIV virus.
These figures do, admittedly exclude one category of intravenous drug users,
the only element among the female population genuinely at risk from
HIV/AIDS. This, on the other hand, has nothing to do with SEX. And Durex
cannot help to reduce the risks for these unfortunate auto-injectors.
For some reason, however, Elle, in association with Durex, have not seen fit
to inform their readers of the true risks of AIDS to women. Instead they are
jointly promoting a new condom for women. According to the Elle editorial,
'Durex have come up with Assure, a condom that still retains the high
quality and reliability of Durex, but which is packaged discreetly and
stylishly . . . no need to wince if they drop out of your handbag.' Handbag?
Whatever happened to the symbolic briefcase?
Doubtless Durex will succeed in its aim to increase the acceptabilty and
sales of its product. But I still think that magazines should not get into
bed with condom manufacturers. The readers have no protection.
Dominic Lawson is editor of The Spectator
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
