<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / US moves carrier into Gulf: UN weapons inspection team
prepares to return to Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS at the UN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US has moved the aircraft carrier America into the Gulf, as the United
Nations prepares for an intensified effort to force Iraq to co-operate in
eliminating its weapons of mass destruction.
The move was disclosed as a UN inspection team prepared to return to Baghdad
next week to continue its mission to track down Iraqi ballistic missile
arsenals.
US defence department officials said the aircraft carrier, which has about
80 warplanes, entered the Gulf on Thursday with an escort of a cruiser, a
frigate and two supply ships.
Officials cautioned that the US had maintained a considerable naval presence
in the Gulf region for some time. The America was not the first US aircraft
carrier to enter the Gulf since the end of the allied military operation
that drove Iraq out of Kuwait last year.
They said the US had 22 naval vessels in the Gulf, along with seven in the
Mediterranean and five in the Red Sea and a strong naval presence would
remain in the region as long as was necessary to enforce the UN economic
embargo on Iraq.
The latest move is regarded as a public display of US determination to put
pressure on the regime of President Saddam Hussein, rather than a militarily
significant deployment. The US in fact already has more than enough
warplanes in place to strike at Iraqi targets if necessary.
Although options are considered limited, President George Bush has said he
would 'contemplate all alternatives' to press Iraq to obey UN orders. Mr
John Major has indicated Britain does not rule out a military strike if Iraq
defies the UN.
The UN Security Council clashed with Mr Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime
minister, at a meeting in New York this week over what the council said was
Iraq's continued refusal to comply with terms of the Gulf war ceasefire.
Visiting Iraqi experts led by General Mohamed Rashid Amir, a deputy minister
of heavy industry, continued talks last night with UN officials in charge of
the programme to dismantle Iraq's most dangerous weapons.
Mr Rolf Ekeus, head of the programme, intends to despatch UN inspectors to
Baghdad next week for another attempt to locate and eliminate the remainder
of the ballistic missile arsenals. More than 60 missiles with a range of
150km or more have been destroyed, but the UN believes there are other
secret stocks.
It was announced last night that talks would resume in Vienna next week on
how to arrange limited sales of Iraqi oil so that the country can buy food
and medicines abroad.
Talks were broken off last month, but the Iraqis agreed this week to make a
new effort to reach an accord. The Iraqis have complained that the deal
would operate in such a way as to violate their sovereignty.
A UN resolution authorising sale of Dollars 1.6bn (Pounds 900m) of Iraqi oil
expires next week. But Mr Diego Arria of Venezuela, Security Council
president, promised a decision would be made next week on whether to extend
the authorisation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
