<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / Volvo winds up import deal with Lex
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLVO, the Swedish car maker, is ending its exclusive import agreement with
Lex Service four years early to take direct control over the distribution of
its vehicles in the UK.
The premature termination of a relationship that goes back 33 years will
cost Volvo more than Pounds 100m. In the heyday of Volvo imports in 1988-89,
more than 80,000 cars a year were sold in the UK - Volvo's second most
important market.
Last year, in a UK car market that was 30 per cent down on its 1989 record
of 2.3m units, Volvo's figure was 47,000 - a share of just under 3 per cent.
Volvo said the ending of the agreement reflected no disappointment in Lex.
It followed the creation of a European marketing section in Brussels.
The Swedish group is following Nissan and Toyota, the Japanese
manufacturers, which have set out to acquire control of their
importer/distributor operations from independent franchises. Volkswagen also
seems determined to take control of VW/Audi in the UK from Lonrho.
Last year Volvo Concessionaires contributed a Pounds 13m operating profit to
Lex's total of Pounds 16.2m. Profit peaked for the import business at about
Pounds 50m in the late 1980s.
Lex's results, announced yesterday, showed a slide in pre-tax profit, after
Pounds 16.5m of interest payments, to Pounds 500,000 on turnover of Pounds
1.32bn. Sir Trevor Chinn, chairman, blamed 'appalling conditions in the UK
motor industry'.
He said that after receiving the Volvo cash and selling its European
electronics components business, the group could have Pounds 70m cash by the
end of this year, on top of an investment worth about Pounds 60m in Arrow
Electronics, an international distribution business.
Lex's share price dropped 30p yesterday to close at 205p, giving the group a
market value of about Pounds 191m.
Results, Page 12
London stocks, Page 17
