FT  14 MAR 92 / 'Supergun' report splits MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs investigating the Iraqi 'supergun' affair split yesterday over a report
which criticises officials but stops short of attacking the intelligence
services and ministers.
The cross-party trade and industry select committee approved by six votes to
four a report to be published on Monday - hours before the Commons rises for
the election.
Four Conservative MPs on the committee tried to block the report, partly
because they believe criticisms implied in it have not been properly
substantiated or investigated.
The Department of Trade and Industry has said it was not fully briefed about
the Iraqi project until March 1990, when eight sections of steel tubing
manufactured by Sheffield Forgemasters were seized by customs officials.
The report blames the DTI and the Ministry of Defence for not pooling
information which, if put together, should have provoked suspicions much
earlier. It suggests, however, the mistakes were innocent, rather than part
of a conspiracy.
