<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / Election 92: Car tax oversight rectified
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday rectified a Budget oversight which could have
proved very costly to car and motorcycle dealers.
Under the proposed Special Car Tax rules dealers had been faced with the
prospect of having to charge customers the new 5 per cent rate to cars and
motorcycles in stock, even though they had already paid the old 10 per cent
rate.
The Retail Motor Industry Federation, the dealers' trade organisation, said
that up to 20,000 cars at various stages in the supply pipeline could have
been caught in the trap at a cost of several million pounds had ministers
not intervened.
Winding up the second reading debate on the Finance Bill to enact the Budget
measures, Mr Francis Maude, the financial secretary to the Treasury, told
the Commons that dealers would be allowed to claim refunds on all such
vehicles.
Customs and Excise has introduced an extra-statutory class concession to
enable refunds of the tax differential to be made in respect of tax-paid
stock which was held by dealers but unsold on March 10.
The announcement came as Vauxhall, Ford's arch rival, responded to deep
price cuts in some of Ford's cheaper car models in the immediate aftermath
of the Budget.
Vauxhall has declined to cut prices but said that it was adding value worth
up to Pounds 850 to some of its models. Mr Bill Ebbert, Vauxhall chairman,
insisted that Vauxhall's cheapest Nova small hatchback was still Pounds 600
cheaper than the equivalent Ford Fiesta in spite of the price cuts.
Letters, Page 11
</TEXT>
