<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / Election 92: Kinnock signals readiness to boost public
spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR looks set to target new spending in next Tuesday's 'shadow budget' at
a boost in capital expenditure on hospitals and schools, along with steps to
encourage private finance for the railways.
The hint on how Labour might reallocate the Pounds 1.8bn spent by the Tories
in Budget tax cuts came in Mr Neil Kinnock's speech to the Scottish Labour
party in Edinburgh yesterday.
So far, Labour has kept silent as to what it might do with the Pounds 1.8bn
'windfall' due from its promise to reverse the government's decision to
raise the public-sector borrowing requirement for a new 20p tax band. But it
has made clear that the money will be spent on new projects leading to
fierce speculation as to where the funds might go.
The party's published Pounds 4.4bn economic programme is already funded by
increases in taxes on the higher paid and the removal of the National
Insurance contribution ceiling on upper band taxpayers. This money will go
on increased pensions and child benefit and on Labour's Pounds 1.1bn
industrial recovery programme.
But in his speech Mr Kinnock suggested that the 'windfall' finance arising
from the tax cuts has been set aside exclusively for education and health -
Labour's 'winning' election issues.
Mr Kinnock said: 'We will take a lead by investing in capital works for the
health service, the education service and for house building to stimulate
the construction and building supply industries.'
He went on to add that Labour would also get private finance into public
railway projects to provide orders for engineering industries.
However, the Labour leader made clear that the number of projects that could
benefit from new cash would be limited. 'It is not an exhaustive list,' he
said.
His comments conform with Labour's commitments to concentrate government
spending on capital schemes rather than social security where it can be
accused of squandering money on consumer spending.
Its central criticism of the Tories' tax cutting budget has centred on the
waste of 'borrowing for consumption' rather than investment. Generalised tax
cuts will merely increasing imports at a time when efforts should be
targetted at employment-intensive sectors such as construction, Labour says.
In another key passage in his speech Mr Kinnock steered a careful path in
tackling the controversial debate over Scotland's future.
Attacking the Nationalists and Tories as 'separatists and centralists', he
said that Labour's plans for an elected parliament would fulfil Labour's
'constitutional contract' with Scotland and maintain the union.
</TEXT>
