FT  14 MAR 92 / Bovis to manage Olympics construction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOVIS, the construction arm of Peninsular &amp; Oriental Steam Navigation (P&amp;O),
the British shipping and property group, has won the contract to manage the
main construction works for 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta, Georgia.
The contract, thought to be worth between Dollars 700m and Dollars 1bn is to
provide sports facilities and accommodation, transport, communications and
other infrastructure.
A spokesman for the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games said that
McDevitt and Street, an Atlanta-based subsidiary of Bovis, had been selected
as lead contractor for the construction programme, but the detail of the
contract was still under negotiation.
It is the latest in a string of large contracts for Bovis which managed the
construction contract for the first phase of the Euro Disney theme park near
Paris and has recently won a Dollars 700m contract to manage the second
phase. It also managed construction of the Canary Wharf tower, Europe's
second tallest building, for Olympia &amp; York in London's former docklands.
