<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / Lloyd's in fresh drive to raise cash from members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, PETER MARTIN and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S of London, the insurance market, is taking special measures to raise
cash from members who have been refusing to pay money, or to meet cash
calls, needed to cover losses.
It has served formal notice on members who have received cash calls that it
will draw down on funds held on deposit or on bank guarantees and letters of
credit to make up any missing money.
A letter dated March 9 sent to Names, the individuals who supply the capital
to the market, by Lloyd's membership department based at Chatham, Kent,
says: 'You will be aware that a number of recent cash calls have met with a
poor response. Accordingly it is necessary to take special measures in order
to accelerate the normal process for the release of Names' deposits to
syndicate funds.'
It continues: 'By formal resolution, the Council of Lloyd's decided on March
4 to pursue this action on a blanket basis'.
An accompanying letter warns Names that, if necessary, 'the Council may,
without giving further notice to you, take steps to draw down on your
deposit for the necessary amount'.
Some 700 Names represented by Mr Michael Freeman, a London solicitor, are
seeking injunctions to prevent Lloyd's drawing down on the deposits all
Names must lodge with their agents when they join. The main letter
specifically mentions this legal action as a cause of 'additional delays' in
raising cash from Names.
A Lloyd's official said, however, that the blanket demand for payment did
not apply to those names represented by Mr Freeman, since a court
undertaking has frozen their deposits until the case is heard later this
month. The official accepted there was a risk that this special demand for
payment could drive other Names to join Mr Freeman's action.
He described the letters as 'precautionary tactics'. He did not know how
many Names were affected though it is believed the number could run into
thousands.
Lloyd's is asking members' agents to forward the formal notice only to those
Names in arrears on cash calls, or without enough cash in their special or
personal reserves to meet the calls outstanding. The notice is being sent to
Names who have applied to Lloyd's Hardship Committee for help, 'pending the
outcome of their application'.
The managers of the syndicates formerly run by Gooda Walker, which have
suffered particularly bad losses, have been unable to collect Pounds 20m of
a Pounds 136m cash call made last year, and have made little progress in
collecting Pounds 101m called this month.
A third letter to Names says: 'You are only required to pay the amount of
the outstanding call(s), and accordingly the Council will only draw down on
your deposit to the extent that it receives formal written notification from
your underwriting agent(s) that you have failed to pay a cash call in full
or part.'
The cash calls are needed for the most part to meet reinsurance claims by
other syndicates, not to pay the original insurance claims. Names on
syndicates managed by Gooda Walker, Feltrim, Rose Thomson Young and
Devonshire face a bill of more than Pounds 700m, over half the market's
total loss for 1989.
Last week, Standard &amp; Poor's the US credit rating agency, infuriated
officials at the Lloyd's Corporation by saying it was concerned that Lloyd's
might face a liquidity crisis, or cash shortage.
Lloyd's dismissed the fears as unfounded. It says that its assets of Pounds
18bn exceed liabilities by Pounds 6bn and that many liabilities arise from
claims which may in some cases not fall due until well into the next
century.
</TEXT>
