<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAR 92 / Kinnock pledges to increase investment: Tories ready to
retaliate with promise to cut taxes and inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, ALISON SMITH and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK set out his central election message yesterday when he
contrasted an exhausted Tory government, bereft of vision, with a Labour
administration pledged to 'invest, invest, invest'.
As Mr John Major prepared to unveil his campaign themes today, Mr Kinnock,
the Labour leader, said his government would 'take the lead' with a
programme of economic measures to bring Britain out of recession and free
the country of the fear of unemployment.
In a passionate speech to Scottish party members, Mr Kinnock quoted his
hero, Aneurin Bevan, saying debts, unemployment and a 'fear of the future'
had halted consumer spending, investment and undermined Britain's
confidence.
Labour's programme would centre on time-limited tax incentives for industry,
training projects and capital works for the National Health Service, schools
and housing.
With two opinion polls today both showing Labour just one percentage point
ahead of the Tories, Mr Major will counter-attack in an address to
supporters in Torquay by stressing his commitment to lower taxes and
inflation. Strategists of both parties are braced for the six opinion polls
to be published tomorrow, already dubbed 'Super Sunday' at Westminster.
Mr Major will tackle head-on the opposition's insistence on the need for a
change after 13 years of the Conservatives. He will say: 'The Labour party
want to change Britain. There would be change all right - short change, for
pensioners as savings shrank, for home owners as interest rates soar.'
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, began his intense election
programme yesterday with flying visits to London, Wales and Scotland. He
urged his opponents to abandon negative campaigning and debate problems
which Britain must address by the end of the century.
At Westminster, MPs rushed through all the stages of a heavily truncated
Finance Bill in preparation for the dissolution of Parliament on Monday.
In his Edinburgh speech, Mr Kinnock combined a personal attack on Mr Major
with an attempt to increase the pressure for a televised debate between the
two leaders. He ridiculed the prime minister for hesitating over the
election date and added: 'It seems he is certain about only one thing: he is
definitely not willing to face me in a television debate.'
Labour strategists claimed the Tories were in 'a shambles' over TV debates
during the campaign. Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, Mr Douglas Hurd,
foreign secretary, and Mr Michael Hesel-tine, environment secretary, have
agreed to head-to-head debates with their Labour shadows.
But Tories argue a debate between the two party leaders would be in a
different league.
Mr Kinnock launched a two-pronged attack on the Tories and Scottish National
party in words carefully phrased to head off support for independence and to
promote Labour's plan for a Scottish parliament.
Mr Major will also address the constitutional future of Scotland today. He
will set out his view of what devolution might entail - not institutional
change or added tiers of government, but of passing power directly to people
by enabling them to take more decisions about their lives.
The Gallup poll for The Daily Telegraph shows Labour down half a percentage
point from last week at 38 per cent, the Tories on 37 (down 1 1/2 points)
and the Liberal Democrats on 20. The Harris poll for the Daily Express,
carried out after the Budget, puts Labour on 40, the Tories on 39 and the
Liberal Democrats on 16.
Election guide, Pages 3-6
Tories accuse Labour of lacking experience
Kinnock set to boost public spending
Ashdown sets hectic pace, Page 8
Polls that move markets, Page 11
</TEXT>
